<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Timber Trade Federation</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:16pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">ubmission </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">from the Timber Trade Federation (LPG 56)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="color:#000080; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Our response focuses around the following question in the Call for Evidence. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Do authorities take sufficient advantage of collaborative and joint procurement opportunities, including those available from central government? In addition, the Committee would welcome information on PFI contracts and their operation with local government.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Through this submission, the TTF would like to highlight the inconsistent nature of timber procurement between different public sector agencies. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This inconsistency stems from the fact that at central government level all departments and national agencies must apply the National Timber Procurement Policy (NTPP- see </span><a href="http://www.cpet.org.uk/uk-government-timber-procurement-policy"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.cpet.org.uk/uk-government-timber-procurement-policy</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">), </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">whil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">st local government departments are not mandated to adopt the policy (although some do optionally). </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The inconsistency causes issues on the ground to our members as suppliers of timber to building contractors who undertake construction work for the government at all levels. Within our membership, approximately 90% of the timber purchased is from certified timber sources (which the NTTP promotes as the preferred option). However, under the rules of certification, if (sub-) contractors do not specify or request certified timber (usually because they perceive they will pay more for it) then the documented chain of custody for such products is often broken (although the timber may be certified). This can cause problems for the government department during project audits for certification. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We particular highlight a useful research report that was published by WWF in 2012 called “Barking up the right Tree” - </span><a href="http://assets.wwf.org.uk/downloads/wwf_timber_report.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://assets.wwf.org.uk/downloads/wwf_timber_report.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The report assesses UK local authorities on their success in procuring legal and sustainable/responsible timber and wood products. It complements previous surveys </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">WWF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> undertook in 2007, 2006, 2001 and 1997.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The results for the UK showed that depending on whether the number of local authorities with a sustainable timber product procurement policy in place was calculated as a proportion of the total number of local authorities in the UK or as a proportion of the total number of local authorities in the UK who responded, the figure was either 16% or 57%</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>